headline: 'The Five' on Biden's speech to NATO

utterances.speaker: NEIL CAVUTO, FOX NEWS ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: That that's the kind of stuff that could end it. We'll see you tomorrow. THE FIVE is now.

utterances.speaker: JEANINE PIRRO, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Judge Jeanine Pirro, along with Jessica Tarlov, Jesse Watters, Katie Pavlich, and Greg Gutfeld. It's five o'clock in New York City, and this is THE FIVE. President -- President Biden embarrassing himself on the world stage while trying to show NATO is united against Russia. Biden in Poland today visiting U.S. troops and refugees. That comes after the commander-in-chief directly contradicted what his own administration has been saying for weeks about sanctions deterring Russia.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.sentences: Let's get something straight, do you remember if you covered me from the very beginning I did not say that in fact, the sanctions would deter him. Sanctions never deter. You keep talking about that. Sanctions never deter.

utterances.speaker: UNKNOWN
utterances.sentences: Do you believe the actions will have an impact and make Russia change course in Ukraine?

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: That's not what I said. You are playing a game with me.

utterances.speaker: UNKNOWN
utterances.sentences: The president believes that sanctions are intended to deter.

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS, VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.sentences: The purpose of the sanctions has always been, and continues to be deterrence.

utterances.speaker: ANTONY BLINKEN, U.S. SECRETARY OF STATE
utterances.sentences: The purpose of the sanctions in the first instance is to try to deter Russia from going to war.

utterances.speaker: JEN PSAKI, WHITE HOUSE PRESS SECRETARY
utterances.sentences: We do see them as having a deterrent impact.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: And now Biden is causing even more confusion overseas by telling American troops in Poland that they may soon be sent off to Ukraine.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: Ukrainian people have a lot of backbone, they have a lot of guts. And I'm sure you're observing it. And I don't mean just in military. And you are going to see when you're there and (Inaudible) have been there. You are going to see, you're going to see women, young people stand -- standing in the middle of -- in front of a damn tank who's just saying I'm not leaving. I'm holding my ground.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: The White House quickly coming out to mop up Joe's mess insisting American troops won't be going to Ukraine. All right, I'll start with you, Greg. So, we've got this constant back and forth between the president and the White House. Let's talk about sending troops to Ukraine. He is talking to the 82nd Airborne. He is literally over there in Eastern Europe and telling them they will be there and you will witness it. He even use that verb as well, see it.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, FOX NEWS CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I don't know what the hell he was talking about. That is -- that is -- it's pretty scary. I mean, when Trump would say something that was considered rash, it was directly true. That's directionally insane because it's running complete 100 miles away from the truth or at least, or maybe that is the truth and maybe we're being lied to, we don't know. When Joe talks to the world you feel a kind of a mild embarrassment like when you go out to dinner with a relative who is not quite all there and you hope that she doesn't snap at the waitress or conk out at the dessert tray. But what you see is what you get. It's not like, it's like you always heard about Trump being different behind the scenes. He was like a -- he was like a presidential mallet in reserve, party in the front, but serious in the back so he would flatter a leader but then get the brass tacks somewhere else. But now there's a story emerging or maybe it's just a theory I made up because it's Friday. You know Putin took Crimea under Obama and invaded Ukraine under Joe. And why is that? Because the administrations are essentially the same and they have the same predictable nature. So what was -- what was that gap in between? It was Trump. Why did Putin hold off? Because Trump's brand is unpredictability. How can anybody deny this? Putin was like, maybe I better not do it while that guy is around because who knows what he is going to do, he might ball my palace. So right now he --Biden is kind of a hood ornament for the Obama administration and knew that he could pull it off. And then he invades which is a clear violation of international law, it causes a lot of brutality because well, he knew he could.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: Maybe he was being unpredictable.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Yes, yes. Well, he was certainly unpredictable as it relates to his claims that sanctions would never deter Russia from going after Ukraine, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You don't hand Biden a hot mic next to a war zone. The guy is --

utterances.speaker: KATIE PAVLICH, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- asked from this trip, it's Friday, you strap a teleprompter to his eyeballs and you let it rip. This, we can't risk something this crazy and then the White House comes and mops it up like he's some drunk celebrity. What my client meant to say was the exact opposite of what he did say. And it's not just that, it's the deterrence they're on the wrong page. Remember when he said, you know, if they take a tiny chunk of Ukraine, maybe we won't do anything.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Or how about he shares the intel with the Chinese, the Chinese just hand it to the Kremlin. The MiG fiasco. The Russians and the Saudis won't take his phone calls. This is a mess. And they act like it's not a mess is a real problem. Right now, we don't know if Biden misspoke and he is not planning on that or he's planning on it and he slipped. Now, how scary is that? And you got to think the Russians are looking at this six ways from Sunday trying to figure out what's going on here. We don't know what's going on here either.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: OK, Katie, there is a sound I want you to take a listen to and we'll come to you on the other side of it.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: Putin has issued Russia's energy resources, that's of course manipulated its neighbors as Saudi has used it. He's used the profits to drive his war machine. That's why earlier this month I announced the United States would ban all imports of Russia energy to make it clear that the American people would not part of -- the United States and the European Union are going to work together to take concrete measures to reduce dependence on natural gas.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: OK. Now what's interesting about that, Katie, is that the Treasury Department has assured Wall Street that it can still trade Russian oil and gas through June 24th.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: So what does he mean? Does he mean anything that he says?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: He is talking about the ban on imports of Russian gas and oil but the sanctions on that don't go in place until June unless and maybe if they even do that. You all remember that Donald Trump, President Donald Trump in 2019 had a very harsh meeting with the head of NATO talking about this exact same thing. You are spending money with Russia, they are going to manipulate you and use it as a weapon. They laughed at him and said he is being too harsh and didn't want the alliance to maintain its credibility. When really, he was saying, your decisions in terms with business and who you allow to control your energy sector are going to hold you hostage once things get hot and now that's exactly where we are. On the communication standpoint, miscommunications lead to miscalculations which cause wars. That's how wars start. And then communication from this administration has been so sloppy when it comes to what they say, what they actually mean. And bringing up President Obama in 2014, you know, in Syria the president there called Obama's bluff when he drew a red line and he didn't follow up with it and Russia also called his bluff and they went into Syria and they've been there ever since helping with the civilian annihilation in that country. And now they are doing it in Ukraine knowing that Joe Biden says a lot of things that maybe he doesn't mean or if he's unclear about it. President Trump he said what he meant and they took them seriously. That's not the case in this situation and people who are in the United States military stationed in NATO countries happening right now are very nervous about a misstatement turning into a miscalculation --

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: True.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: -- in a very volatile situation.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: You know, and Jessica, Biden has been boasting that he's going to get Europe off od Russian oil even though we're maxed out on our domestic natural gas production. And he's not increasing the supply. How is he going to do that?

utterances.speaker: JESSICA TARLOV, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.sentences: I think that he's going to have to. He did say when we was in Pennsylvania that he wasn't completely anti- fracking. I mean, we only had 3 percent of our oil coming from Russia in the first place. But what he's trying to manage is, you know, 10, 15, 20 countries and how they are going to have a relationship with Russia.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: How about he just manage this country and get us oil?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Well, he is. But -- but this is not just about us. We just saw that a Saudi refinery got blown up today and the price of oil spiked right back into $113 a barrel, it was down to $96 just a few days ago. There are obviously global factors that's obviously not related to what's going on in Ukraine/Russia at all and that can happen and that can slash our supply. I understand what you want me to say is that he is just going to frack us into oblivion and then we'll be completely energy independent --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: -- and everything will be fine.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: I want you to say anything.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Say whatever you want to say.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Well, I said that because, well, Greg at least wanted me to say that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I did.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Yes. But I want to say something about the communications part of this. I don't think that the 82nd Airborne or anyone is confused about what we're doing about troops because he misspoke. I do think that what he was saying was, by being in this region you are going to see the strength of the Ukrainians. They are streaming into Poland right now. Right? Walking across the borders. We hear about mothers walking with three pets and five children picking up kids by the side of the road. I think that's what he was talking about. And it does seem like everybody is unified here. And I would put it to the table, what would our Republican president or someone besides Biden who you think is more confident be doing any differently at this point? Because to my mind, all I see is that your option is that we're putting troops or putting boots on the ground and then we're possibly heading to a nuclear war or we are continuing on this path.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: You give them the -- you give them the S-300. You give them the Iron Dome.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: But that can -- that can target war.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: We should cower in the corner because we are afraid of what Putin is going to say?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Well, we're not cowering. John Kirby has even said that we are doing more than we're talking about publicly, which is how you want your government to operate.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: They're still -- they're still leveling the country. They're still leveling.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: They're leveling the country but there are also, we'll hear about that Putin's inner circle is collapsing around him. By the way, that's the effect of sanctions, right? Those are really rich people who are having their money sanctioned. We hear about there was a brigade where Russian troops killed their own commander because they didn't want to fight this war anymore. And that's all very meaningful. I'm not -- I'm not saying tomorrow this will be over, but I think it's really --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Say the thing we wanted you to say.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Coming up --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: I already said fracking into oblivion.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Coming up, bare shelves. Biden is about to make a big comeback after what the president just said.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Americans may -- may be facing more economic hardships. In addition to rising gas prices and inflation, President Biden now warning the country to get ready for an incoming food shortage because of the war in Ukraine.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: With regard to food shortage, yes, we did. We -- let's talk about food shortages. And it's going to be real. The price of these sanctions is not just imposed upon Russia. It's imposed upon on awful lot of countries as well including European countries and our country as well.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: According to a Fox News poll, voters are getting fed up and blaming the president and his policies for making the economy worse with 53 percent saying that he is at fault. Katie --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Yes, ma'am.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: I'm old enough to remember when everyone was complaining that Biden wasn't shooting straight about these issues. And he's obfuscating and now he is telling the truth. Shouldn't this actually be applauded?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: I mean, it's him telling the truth should be applauded, but the fact that we are in America in the year 2020 with a food shortage should not be applauded as a result of his policies. So, I'm old enough to remember that last summer Jen Psaki stood at the White House podium and laughed and mocked the idea that Americans were having their treadmills delayed too late when there was a supply chain crisis. And I said on the show wait until people can't get food to their homes and you're going to have a way more serious problem. Now, now here we are. And it's proving that Americans and people all over the world in their own countries have to start thinking about producing their own country sustaining products, whether it's fertilizer that we're now saying there is a shortage of so food can't be grown. Food that we import from the rest of the world. Energy, antibiotics, medicine, personal protective gear that we saw China take a monopoly of during the pandemic. So it raises this idea that we can always rely on other countries to make sure that we can sustain ourselves here at home. And President Biden says it's going to be a real thing without offering a solution and saying, but don't worry, I have a plan to combat this coming food shortage. And this is what my administration is going to do. he throws it out there it's like a bomb, like, get ready America. Without some kind of plan to try and, you know, mitigate the disaster that he says is coming.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: So Russia's supplies I think it's 40 percent of the world's wheat. What kind of plan could he throw out there this quickly? I'm not saying that we don't have to become more independent as it were, but what is a viable solution because this just isn't us?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Vote free. I don't know. I don't know.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Sally (Inaudible).

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes. Why don't win -- why don't Democrats win elections when this always happens. It's like they can't -- we know they can't handle foreign policy. We know they suck at the economy. The only thing they can do is raise our taxes, to spend that money on programs that then expand the problem. I'm old enough to remember Jimmy Carter. And I miss him. This is the consequence of the laptop cover up. Jessica, do you like Ashton Kutcher?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Not recently.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Did you enjoy the movie "The Butterfly -- the Butterfly Effect," do you remember that movie?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: I do remember it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Let's do the butterfly effect here using the laptop. Number one, the New York Post publishes the laptop story. And then tech and media and the Democrats collude together to bury it and therefore, we don't know about the big guy, i.e., Joe Biden and that corruption. Right? So that -- that is the cabal that as stated in Time magazine. So instead of losing the election which you would have if that was public, he wins the election, thanks to the cabal, and then the unpredictable force of Trump is missing. And then if we have Obama part 3, the coon -- the cocoon addition, and then Putin sees that opening use the U.S./Ukraine agreement re NATO on November 10 to invade. Famine. That's the butterfly effect. It goes all the way back to the laptop cover- up. You can publish that and make it into a movie. It's Friday.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Are you going to that movie, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, the book was better than the movie. And I never say --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: You said that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Do you agree?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I know. I do agree.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: They do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So I have a wheat guy, do you want to hear what my wheat guy says?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Do you have a wheat guy?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I have a wheat guy.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Wow.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: My wheat guy says that the last time this happened in 2010, wheat prices doubled and yet, the Arab Spring and five governments got knocked off. And you had the Syrian Civil War. Now they are saying it's going to be six times as big of a price jump. So he sees civil unrest in the Mideast, Sub-Saharan Africa, Southeast Asia and Brazil because of this, because you also got the fertilizer scarcity. And America is not going to be that bad because we have a lot of wheat producers and we ask -- we export a lot of money a lot of wheat. So we're going to have to bail out the farmers, he predicts, throw a lot of money, cut a check to the farmers. And he says every time wheat prices doubles it adds a quarter to a loaf of bread. So start saving because things are about to get very expensive. My wheat guy is also my geopolitical guy. And he says you are going to have a food shortage, an energy crisis, and a global recession all in the next two years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Should we get fat right now?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Let's go --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- and be like squirrels and just put it on so we can get through.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: I'm way ahead of you, Greg.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: You know --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Your wheat guy says what?

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: I don't have a wheat guy. You know, I want -- because I'm thinking of going gluten-free anyway, but I think you're right, Greg. The -- look, the crazy part of all of this is that we are sanctioning or we think for sanctioning Putin, right, to deter him from -- from fighting the war in Ukraine except we're not really sanctioning him because it doesn't really, it doesn't seem like it's doing any good. But now we've got a real issue. And that is that there is going to be world hunger. I mean, that's what it looks like. And I don't mean to, you know, to be, you know, someone bringing gloom and doom. But you would think that, you know, we wouldn't -- that we would try to protect whether it's a wheat deal or fertilizer or whatever needs to be protected, recognizing that that is, that can create world chaos and it can create, as you said, you know, governments being overthrown, leaders being overthrown. I mean, we're in for a bit of a mess because this one guy, Putin, this genocidal maniac decided that he wanted to go into a country and just level it and kill everybody. I mean, to me, it's so obvious. I mean, the Russian people can't be in any way be in favor of him. If the Russian people are now starting to say that they are killing their own generals in Ukraine, then you know, he's got to go. It's the only thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Got to go. So do we, right?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: We absolutely do.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'll take care.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: You want to read my (Inaudible).

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Throw it in, let's go, let's go.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: OK, coming up, President Biden facing a new potential crisis, this time coming from within his own party.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: President Biden dealing with a landslide of problems in his own party just added more fuel to the fire. Squad leader Alexandria Ocasio- Cortez warning Biden to do what the far left wants or face the consequences.

utterances.speaker: REP. ALEXANDRIA OCASIO-CORTEZ (D-NY)
utterances.sentences: It is Biden's power and ability to cancel student debt and nobody else. We need to acknowledge that this isn't just about middle-of-the-road and increasingly narrowband of independent voters. But this is really about the collapse and support among young people, among the Democratic base feeling like they are not -- they worked overtime to get this president elected and they aren't necessarily being seen.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: But Biden isn't the only one in the part that AOC is going after. And the radical socialist also taking the opportunity to attack Joe Manchin.

utterances.speaker: OCASIO-CORTEZ
utterances.sentences: So, I'm mad. This idea of, if we coddle someone's ego then they're going to, they're going to say yes. And if it hasn't worked in two years why are we going to continue doing that when there's an election this November?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: So, Jesse, isn't AOC like the child who wants to eat candy for dinner and Joe Manchin is the Democrat who is like, actually you need to eat vegetables for dinner and then a tantrum is thrown, and ultimately the adults wins the argument.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Manchin loves when he's attacked by AOC. It looks so good in West Virginia. The Republicans, Democrats and independents love that and makes them look great. AOC just called the president a fink. She said we were for Bernie, then Clyburn cut the deal with the black vote. OK, you got the nomination, Joe, we turned out, put you in the White House. Where is our scratch? Right? Where is our student loan forgiveness, where's our green new deal, give me what I want, what I earned. And Biden is not providing that. And it's also funny because she has student loans. So she is asking for a bailout. Yet, doesn't she drive a Tesla, she was just partying in Miami Beach --

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- and she's all getting photographed on the red carpet so she doesn't need the bailout. But here is the thing. This didn't sound to me like, you better worry about your base, Joe. This sounded like a threat. This sounded like you better give me my money or this base is going to turn and it's going to turn hard. That's what I saw. But I'd be pissed too if I was a young Democrat. I mean, what do you want? Infrastructure? You live in the city. You don't need that. Free COVID relief? COVID can't kill you, you're 30.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: They want a new bridge, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Judge, go ahead, the language and the threatening.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Yes. You know what's amazing? For someone who is in Congress for a legislator to say what we can't get done in Congress just sign an executive order. Just forget about the fact that we exist.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes. Right.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.sentences: Sign an executive order. And if you can take care of the -- of us with this, child care and the prescription drug prices, and if you can't get rid of student loans, then we're going -- we're coming after you. You're not coming after him because, in the end, you're not going to vote Republican.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Right. Right, exactly. Greg, student loan bailout bails out a lot of people like her who don't need the money and --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, I know Jessica wants me to say I'm 100 percent behind it, but I'm not. Apparently, she has a business degree, doesn't she?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: She does.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, how do you -- how -- she's never explained how you cancel student debt. I mean, who's going to -- who's going to cover the cost of that? The university could eat the loans. I would love that. But they're not going to want to do that. Could you imagine that? That'll make them Republicans.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The moment that happens. The banks could eat the loans, and they're outrageous interest rates. But the banks, they got bailed out. They never have anything to worry about. So, she's expecting the viewer, you, me, everybody, to foot the bill of upper-middle class over-educated, mostly white liberals. That's -- the people that actually could afford to pay -- no, you're going to get the truck drivers and the secretaries and the waiters to pay the tuitions for that. It's not going to happen. It's not going to happen. And what about all of the parents and the students who paid their loans who did the right thing, shouldn't they get refunds then? If anybody deserves a bailout, it's the people who do the right thing, and not the people who do the wrong thing. I would like to see that.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: So, Jessica, who is more in touch with the Democratic base, Joe Manchin of West Virginia or AOC from New York City?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: Neither. Someone more in the middle is more in touch with the Democratic base.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She's pulled the middle to the -- so you think the middle -

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: I still think that elections in this country, and this has been true for almost all the time, are one in the center. And that's why Joe Biden was able to pull this off against Trump in 2020. That's why we saw that huge surge of moderate Democrats that the 2018 election that brought in the camo wave where we had all of these representatives who had served whether in the CIA or gone abroad and fought in Iraq and Afghanistan. And I think that's really where the country is. Now, I think that AOC is showing off two things. One, her true values. She does believe that student debt should be canceled. She believes in the Green New Deal, etcetera. But she also --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Believes aren't enough. You need a -- you need a system.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.sentences: No. But this is also performative because AOC is going to fall in line just like she did in 2020 when the midterms come around. But she needs to have those sound bites. She needs to show her base of voters who are these younger environmentalists that she has been advocating for those policies. And just a little something about Joe Manchin who does irritate me from time to time. We wouldn't have anything that we have right now without Joe Manchin. There is no other Democrat on the planet who was winning in West Virginia. He just announced today that he's voting for Judge Jackson. That is her confirmation unless something happens with Kyrsten Sinema. And Joe Manchin outran Donald Trump in West Virginia. That is a feat beyond belief. utterances.utterance: Or how about he shares the intel with the Chinese, the Chinese just hand it to the Kremlin. The MiG fiasco. The Russians and the Saudis won't take his phone calls. This is a mess. And they act like it's not a mess is a real problem. Right now, we don't know if Biden misspoke and he is not planning on that or he's planning on it and he slipped. Now, how scary is that? And you got to think the Russians are looking at this six ways from Sunday trying to figure out what's going on here. We don't know what's going on here either.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: OK, Katie, there is a sound I want you to take a listen to and we'll come to you on the other side of it.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: Putin has issued Russia's energy resources, that's of course manipulated its neighbors as Saudi has used it. He's used the profits to drive his war machine. That's why earlier this month I announced the United States would ban all imports of Russia energy to make it clear that the American people would not part of -- the United States and the European Union are going to work together to take concrete measures to reduce dependence on natural gas.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: OK. Now what's interesting about that, Katie, is that the Treasury Department has assured Wall Street that it can still trade Russian oil and gas through June 24th.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: So what does he mean? Does he mean anything that he says?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: He is talking about the ban on imports of Russian gas and oil but the sanctions on that don't go in place until June unless and maybe if they even do that. You all remember that Donald Trump, President Donald Trump in 2019 had a very harsh meeting with the head of NATO talking about this exact same thing. You are spending money with Russia, they are going to manipulate you and use it as a weapon. They laughed at him and said he is being too harsh and didn't want the alliance to maintain its credibility. When really, he was saying, your decisions in terms with business and who you allow to control your energy sector are going to hold you hostage once things get hot and now that's exactly where we are. On the communication standpoint, miscommunications lead to miscalculations which cause wars. That's how wars start. And then communication from this administration has been so sloppy when it comes to what they say, what they actually mean. And bringing up President Obama in 2014, you know, in Syria the president there called Obama's bluff when he drew a red line and he didn't follow up with it and Russia also called his bluff and they went into Syria and they've been there ever since helping with the civilian annihilation in that country. And now they are doing it in Ukraine knowing that Joe Biden says a lot of things that maybe he doesn't mean or if he's unclear about it. President Trump he said what he meant and they took them seriously. That's not the case in this situation and people who are in the United States military stationed in NATO countries happening right now are very nervous about a misstatement turning into a miscalculation --

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: True.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: -- in a very volatile situation.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: You know, and Jessica, Biden has been boasting that he's going to get Europe off od Russian oil even though we're maxed out on our domestic natural gas production. And he's not increasing the supply. How is he going to do that?

utterances.speaker: JESSICA TARLOV, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.utterance: I think that he's going to have to. He did say when we was in Pennsylvania that he wasn't completely anti- fracking. I mean, we only had 3 percent of our oil coming from Russia in the first place. But what he's trying to manage is, you know, 10, 15, 20 countries and how they are going to have a relationship with Russia.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: How about he just manage this country and get us oil?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Well, he is. But -- but this is not just about us. We just saw that a Saudi refinery got blown up today and the price of oil spiked right back into $113 a barrel, it was down to $96 just a few days ago. There are obviously global factors that's obviously not related to what's going on in Ukraine/Russia at all and that can happen and that can slash our supply. I understand what you want me to say is that he is just going to frack us into oblivion and then we'll be completely energy independent --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: -- and everything will be fine.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: I want you to say anything.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Really?

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Say whatever you want to say.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Well, I said that because, well, Greg at least wanted me to say that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I did.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Yes. But I want to say something about the communications part of this. I don't think that the 82nd Airborne or anyone is confused about what we're doing about troops because he misspoke. I do think that what he was saying was, by being in this region you are going to see the strength of the Ukrainians. They are streaming into Poland right now. Right? Walking across the borders. We hear about mothers walking with three pets and five children picking up kids by the side of the road. I think that's what he was talking about. And it does seem like everybody is unified here. And I would put it to the table, what would our Republican president or someone besides Biden who you think is more confident be doing any differently at this point? Because to my mind, all I see is that your option is that we're putting troops or putting boots on the ground and then we're possibly heading to a nuclear war or we are continuing on this path.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: You give them the -- you give them the S-300. You give them the Iron Dome.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: But that can -- that can target war.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: We should cower in the corner because we are afraid of what Putin is going to say?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Well, we're not cowering. John Kirby has even said that we are doing more than we're talking about publicly, which is how you want your government to operate.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: They're still -- they're still leveling the country. They're still leveling.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: They're leveling the country but there are also, we'll hear about that Putin's inner circle is collapsing around him. By the way, that's the effect of sanctions, right? Those are really rich people who are having their money sanctioned. We hear about there was a brigade where Russian troops killed their own commander because they didn't want to fight this war anymore. And that's all very meaningful. I'm not -- I'm not saying tomorrow this will be over, but I think it's really --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Say the thing we wanted you to say.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Coming up --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: I already said fracking into oblivion.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Coming up, bare shelves. Biden is about to make a big comeback after what the president just said.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Americans may -- may be facing more economic hardships. In addition to rising gas prices and inflation, President Biden now warning the country to get ready for an incoming food shortage because of the war in Ukraine.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: With regard to food shortage, yes, we did. We -- let's talk about food shortages. And it's going to be real. The price of these sanctions is not just imposed upon Russia. It's imposed upon on awful lot of countries as well including European countries and our country as well.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: According to a Fox News poll, voters are getting fed up and blaming the president and his policies for making the economy worse with 53 percent saying that he is at fault. Katie --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes, ma'am.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: I'm old enough to remember when everyone was complaining that Biden wasn't shooting straight about these issues. And he's obfuscating and now he is telling the truth. Shouldn't this actually be applauded?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I mean, it's him telling the truth should be applauded, but the fact that we are in America in the year 2020 with a food shortage should not be applauded as a result of his policies. So, I'm old enough to remember that last summer Jen Psaki stood at the White House podium and laughed and mocked the idea that Americans were having their treadmills delayed too late when there was a supply chain crisis. And I said on the show wait until people can't get food to their homes and you're going to have a way more serious problem. Now, now here we are. And it's proving that Americans and people all over the world in their own countries have to start thinking about producing their own country sustaining products, whether it's fertilizer that we're now saying there is a shortage of so food can't be grown. Food that we import from the rest of the world. Energy, antibiotics, medicine, personal protective gear that we saw China take a monopoly of during the pandemic. So it raises this idea that we can always rely on other countries to make sure that we can sustain ourselves here at home. And President Biden says it's going to be a real thing without offering a solution and saying, but don't worry, I have a plan to combat this coming food shortage. And this is what my administration is going to do. he throws it out there it's like a bomb, like, get ready America. Without some kind of plan to try and, you know, mitigate the disaster that he says is coming.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: So Russia's supplies I think it's 40 percent of the world's wheat. What kind of plan could he throw out there this quickly? I'm not saying that we don't have to become more independent as it were, but what is a viable solution because this just isn't us?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Vote free. I don't know. I don't know.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Sally (Inaudible).

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Yes. Why don't win -- why don't Democrats win elections when this always happens. It's like they can't -- we know they can't handle foreign policy. We know they suck at the economy. The only thing they can do is raise our taxes, to spend that money on programs that then expand the problem. I'm old enough to remember Jimmy Carter. And I miss him. This is the consequence of the laptop cover up. Jessica, do you like Ashton Kutcher?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Not recently.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you enjoy the movie "The Butterfly -- the Butterfly Effect," do you remember that movie?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: I do remember it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Let's do the butterfly effect here using the laptop. Number one, the New York Post publishes the laptop story. And then tech and media and the Democrats collude together to bury it and therefore, we don't know about the big guy, i.e., Joe Biden and that corruption. Right? So that -- that is the cabal that as stated in Time magazine. So instead of losing the election which you would have if that was public, he wins the election, thanks to the cabal, and then the unpredictable force of Trump is missing. And then if we have Obama part 3, the coon -- the cocoon addition, and then Putin sees that opening use the U.S./Ukraine agreement re NATO on November 10 to invade. Famine. That's the butterfly effect. It goes all the way back to the laptop cover- up. You can publish that and make it into a movie. It's Friday.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Are you going to that movie, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, the book was better than the movie. And I never say --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: You said that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Do you agree?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know. I do agree.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: They do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So I have a wheat guy, do you want to hear what my wheat guy says?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Do you have a wheat guy?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I have a wheat guy.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: My wheat guy says that the last time this happened in 2010, wheat prices doubled and yet, the Arab Spring and five governments got knocked off. And you had the Syrian Civil War. Now they are saying it's going to be six times as big of a price jump. So he sees civil unrest in the Mideast, Sub-Saharan Africa, Southeast Asia and Brazil because of this, because you also got the fertilizer scarcity. And America is not going to be that bad because we have a lot of wheat producers and we ask -- we export a lot of money a lot of wheat. So we're going to have to bail out the farmers, he predicts, throw a lot of money, cut a check to the farmers. And he says every time wheat prices doubles it adds a quarter to a loaf of bread. So start saving because things are about to get very expensive. My wheat guy is also my geopolitical guy. And he says you are going to have a food shortage, an energy crisis, and a global recession all in the next two years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Should we get fat right now?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Let's go --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- and be like squirrels and just put it on so we can get through.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: I'm way ahead of you, Greg.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: You know --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Your wheat guy says what?

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: I don't have a wheat guy. You know, I want -- because I'm thinking of going gluten-free anyway, but I think you're right, Greg. The -- look, the crazy part of all of this is that we are sanctioning or we think for sanctioning Putin, right, to deter him from -- from fighting the war in Ukraine except we're not really sanctioning him because it doesn't really, it doesn't seem like it's doing any good. But now we've got a real issue. And that is that there is going to be world hunger. I mean, that's what it looks like. And I don't mean to, you know, to be, you know, someone bringing gloom and doom. But you would think that, you know, we wouldn't -- that we would try to protect whether it's a wheat deal or fertilizer or whatever needs to be protected, recognizing that that is, that can create world chaos and it can create, as you said, you know, governments being overthrown, leaders being overthrown. I mean, we're in for a bit of a mess because this one guy, Putin, this genocidal maniac decided that he wanted to go into a country and just level it and kill everybody. I mean, to me, it's so obvious. I mean, the Russian people can't be in any way be in favor of him. If the Russian people are now starting to say that they are killing their own generals in Ukraine, then you know, he's got to go. It's the only thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Got to go. So do we, right?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: We absolutely do.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'll take care.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: You want to read my (Inaudible).

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Throw it in, let's go, let's go.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: OK, coming up, President Biden facing a new potential crisis, this time coming from within his own party.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: President Biden dealing with a landslide of problems in his own party just added more fuel to the fire. Squad leader Alexandria Ocasio- Cortez warning Biden to do what the far left wants or face the consequences.

utterances.speaker: REP. ALEXANDRIA OCASIO-CORTEZ (D-NY)
utterances.utterance: It is Biden's power and ability to cancel student debt and nobody else. We need to acknowledge that this isn't just about middle-of-the-road and increasingly narrowband of independent voters. But this is really about the collapse and support among young people, among the Democratic base feeling like they are not -- they worked overtime to get this president elected and they aren't necessarily being seen.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But Biden isn't the only one in the part that AOC is going after. And the radical socialist also taking the opportunity to attack Joe Manchin.

utterances.speaker: OCASIO-CORTEZ
utterances.utterance: So, I'm mad. This idea of, if we coddle someone's ego then they're going to, they're going to say yes. And if it hasn't worked in two years why are we going to continue doing that when there's an election this November?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, Jesse, isn't AOC like the child who wants to eat candy for dinner and Joe Manchin is the Democrat who is like, actually you need to eat vegetables for dinner and then a tantrum is thrown, and ultimately the adults wins the argument.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Manchin loves when he's attacked by AOC. It looks so good in West Virginia. The Republicans, Democrats and independents love that and makes them look great. AOC just called the president a fink. She said we were for Bernie, then Clyburn cut the deal with the black vote. OK, you got the nomination, Joe, we turned out, put you in the White House. Where is our scratch? Right? Where is our student loan forgiveness, where's our green new deal, give me what I want, what I earned. And Biden is not providing that. And it's also funny because she has student loans. So she is asking for a bailout. Yet, doesn't she drive a Tesla, she was just partying in Miami Beach --

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and she's all getting photographed on the red carpet so she doesn't need the bailout. But here is the thing. This didn't sound to me like, you better worry about your base, Joe. This sounded like a threat. This sounded like you better give me my money or this base is going to turn and it's going to turn hard. That's what I saw. But I'd be pissed too if I was a young Democrat. I mean, what do you want? Infrastructure? You live in the city. You don't need that. Free COVID relief? COVID can't kill you, you're 30.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: They want a new bridge, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Judge, go ahead, the language and the threatening.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Yes. You know what's amazing? For someone who is in Congress for a legislator to say what we can't get done in Congress just sign an executive order. Just forget about the fact that we exist.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Right.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: Sign an executive order. And if you can take care of the -- of us with this, child care and the prescription drug prices, and if you can't get rid of student loans, then we're going -- we're coming after you. You're not coming after him because, in the end, you're not going to vote Republican.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right. Right, exactly. Greg, student loan bailout bails out a lot of people like her who don't need the money and --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I know Jessica wants me to say I'm 100 percent behind it, but I'm not. Apparently, she has a business degree, doesn't she?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: She does.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. So, how do you -- how -- she's never explained how you cancel student debt. I mean, who's going to -- who's going to cover the cost of that? The university could eat the loans. I would love that. But they're not going to want to do that. Could you imagine that? That'll make them Republicans.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The moment that happens. The banks could eat the loans, and they're outrageous interest rates. But the banks, they got bailed out. They never have anything to worry about. So, she's expecting the viewer, you, me, everybody, to foot the bill of upper-middle class over-educated, mostly white liberals. That's -- the people that actually could afford to pay -- no, you're going to get the truck drivers and the secretaries and the waiters to pay the tuitions for that. It's not going to happen. It's not going to happen. And what about all of the parents and the students who paid their loans who did the right thing, shouldn't they get refunds then? If anybody deserves a bailout, it's the people who do the right thing, and not the people who do the wrong thing. I would like to see that.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, Jessica, who is more in touch with the Democratic base, Joe Manchin of West Virginia or AOC from New York City?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Neither. Someone more in the middle is more in touch with the Democratic base.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She's pulled the middle to the -- so you think the middle -

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: I still think that elections in this country, and this has been true for almost all the time, are one in the center. And that's why Joe Biden was able to pull this off against Trump in 2020. That's why we saw that huge surge of moderate Democrats that the 2018 election that brought in the camo wave where we had all of these representatives who had served whether in the CIA or gone abroad and fought in Iraq and Afghanistan. And I think that's really where the country is. Now, I think that AOC is showing off two things. One, her true values. She does believe that student debt should be canceled. She believes in the Green New Deal, etcetera. But she also --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Believes aren't enough. You need a -- you need a system.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: No. But this is also performative because AOC is going to fall in line just like she did in 2020 when the midterms come around. But she needs to have those sound bites. She needs to show her base of voters who are these younger environmentalists that she has been advocating for those policies. And just a little something about Joe Manchin who does irritate me from time to time. We wouldn't have anything that we have right now without Joe Manchin. There is no other Democrat on the planet who was winning in West Virginia. He just announced today that he's voting for Judge Jackson. That is her confirmation unless something happens with Kyrsten Sinema. And Joe Manchin outran Donald Trump in West Virginia. That is a feat beyond belief. So, this idea that you can attack him from the left is a wholly ridiculous. Just let people run their own campaigns. Honestly, every -- on the Republican side, too. If you're in a super right-wing district, go ahead and do it your way. If you're in a moderate district, go ahead and do it your way. Everyone feel a lot happier.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I think that's good advice. All right --

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: You're welcome.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Coming up, call Harris' terrible week may have just gotten even worse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: More drama for Kamala. The Vice President coming off a terrible week in the news from an explosive new book detailing her feud with President Biden to another nonsensical speech on the road. Harris really did her best to distract from all of Biden's shortcomings. But that's nothing new for the VP. She has a rich history of putting her foot in her mouth.

utterances.speaker: LESTER HOLT, ANCHOR, NBC NEWS
utterances.utterance: You haven't been to the border.

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS, VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES
utterances.utterance: And I haven't been to Europe. Ukraine is a country in Europe. It exists next to another country called Russia. A friend in need is a friend in need. The significance of the passage of time, right, the significance of the passage of time. So, when you think about it, there is great significance to the passage of time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And Kamala hiring a new press secretary after her recent staff exodus. But the new spokeswoman deleted over 10,000 tweets before starting the new job. So, we can't cancel her, right, Katie?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I think she's in for the long haul, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The long haul meeting what? Three weeks.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: The next two months. I'm not sure.

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: The next year.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Look, she's had a hard time keeping staff. She had a difficult time in the Senate with her staff there as well. What I found the most interesting about the last two weeks and what's come up about her is this idea that she was very frustrated with President Biden that he would not publicly come out in favor of nuking the filibuster for months on that, and he eventually did come out. But that just proves that she's not only unconvincing to the American public, but behind closed doors to a body like the Senate where she worked, she's unable to be convincing to her peers. And that was a big part of what her agenda was supposed to be. She completely failed on that aspect. And people wonder why she's taking on these far-left issues like abolishing the filibuster. Well, let's not forget, she was the most far-left member of the Senate, including beating up Bernie Sanders before she was picked to be the Vice President was supposed to be payback for people like AOC. So, we'll see. It's typical to watch as we -- as we know. Maybe entertaining for you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's entertaining. I wouldn't call it difficult.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She, Dramala Harris, is a national treasure who provides us with quality entertainment almost every other day. There's not much to laugh about these days in the -- when you turn on the news, but she's kind of become like our Mr. Bean or our Inspector Clouseau, allowing us to laugh at her mistakes or vacuous sojourns into nonsense. Every day is something new and it makes me warm all over. It's funny to us, but could you imagine being that woman being your boss? You know, we can laugh, but it's got -- it's probably worse than working under Kilmeade or you know, working with the judge. But she's -- because you know, she's the worst at work because she comes off as somebody who thinks that actual work is beneath her. And then what happens is she ends up having to do more work on the -- on the other side of the incompetence, when in fact, if you just did the actual job, like if you read the -- what do you call it -- the briefing books. If you read the briefing books, then you probably do less work. But she doesn't do that, so she ends up making a lot of work for everybody and making people unhappy. But I love her with every fiber of my being.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What do you think's really going on here?

utterances.speaker: PIRRO
utterances.utterance: I think -- well, first of all, I want to know who vetted her. I want to know why Joe Biden decided a woman who couldn't get one percent in the presidential law primary was worth it to have as VP. But I think what's going on with her is that she didn't have a stellar time as a senator. And obviously, she's now a national joke. There's nothing that she says that makes sense. I mean, other than we should do what we have been doing regularly every day. And to continue doing what we have would -- I mean, it's just -- it's a joke. But I think that a woman who is wounded and belittled because her cover on Vogue Magazine has her I'm Converse and a pantsuit that she put on herself during a pandemic is -- it doesn't understand the gravity of the job that she has. And I think it's a very sad situation. I do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Jessica, does she ever get out of the joke phase? Because right now she's a joke and she makes a lot of gaffs. Is she ever going to get vengeful? Are we going to see like an angry face or like I give up phase or we're just going to be stuck on this Dramala?

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Like the Marvel evolution of a villain?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: TARLOV
utterances.utterance: Like when does she got her costume or something?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
